Students with a fully remote schedule will also receive their textbooks, calculators, and other school materials at this time. On Friday, September 11th, all FULLY REMOTE elementary students will be able to pick up their device and materials from 9:00-11:00 or 12:00-2:00. Students that are coming for our half day model will be given their device and materials in-person.

The free milk distribution will take place in the high school bus loop on Monday, August 31st between the hours of 10:00 am and 12:00 pm. This donation of free milk will be distributed to any community member until it is gone.

Elementary Update:
- All supply lists have been posted to our school website (under elementary).
- All letters for grades 1-6 are being mailed tomorrow. Your child’s teacher will be listed along with a hard copy of the supply list.
-Kindergarten letters will be mailed out at the end of the week. There will be information regarding our orientation, your child’s teacher and a supply list for the class. Kindergarten will not operate on the regular schedule September 14th. Instead, each family will be assigned a time to arrive for orientation. In order to keep everyone safe, please limit the visit to two family members (in addition to your kindergartener).

Thank you for your patience. It took a lot longer than normal to figure this all out. We’re excited to see everyone in September!

Mrs. Holmes

To Parents/Guardians/Community:

The district will be hosting two additional public meetings with parents, guardians, community members, and stakeholders to address and discuss potential concerns and/or outstanding questions regarding the school reopening plans. The district previously provided public opportunity for discussion on July 30, 2020 and August 10, 2020. The next two opportunities will occur on Tuesday, August 18. 2020. The times for each meeting are;
Meeting Times:
• Meeting #1: 10:00 AM – 11:00 AM
• Meeting #2: 5:00 PM – 6:00 PM
Both meetings will be live and streamed through the district website. A meeting link will be provided on the website. Stakeholders may submit questions ahead of time and throughout the meeting by emailing the District Clerk, Karen Sheets ksheets@westcanada.org. As always, please do not hesitate to contact the district office at 315-845-6800 if you have questions/concerns. Take care and stay safe.

Mr. Shepardson - Superintendent

Dear WCV preK - 6th grade families,

We understand the challenges you may have faced, time you spent and school work you accomplished during the COVID-19 closure. To simply say thank you doesn't seem to be enough. We are sponsoring one yearbook for every preK - 6th grade family. And, to the 6th graders, we'll sponsor you for your own copy.

Again, thank you for all of your efforts and hard work!

Gratefully,
The WCV PTO

post_text:
Hi WCV! The Sora Reading Competition has only two weeks left and I am sad to say that our school has fallen to 10th place. Clinton Elementary continues to be in first place, their students have borrowed 124 books in the past week. I KNOW WE CAN CATCH UP TO THEM!!! Or at least get close. If you haven't logged into Sora yet, now is the time to check it out! There are thousands of books available, I know you will find something you will enjoy reading.

Throughout the week I will be posting book talks and suggestions under the Library section of Google Classroom, if you'd like some ideas. Remember, Sora is still going to be there when school is out so you can borrow and read books all summer if you'd like.

I'd also like to point out that Sora is not just for the elementary students. There are thousands of titles for middle and high school students as well. Not sure how to log in or use Sora? Contact me and I can help you out! 📘📕Mrs. Novak

post_text:
A Message From WCV Elementary

Hello Everyone,

I hope you are all doing well! As the days roll on, it is getting harder and harder to walk through the halls without seeing all of your smiling faces. We miss you very much and can’t wait for this to be over! For now, please make sure you are checking your Google Classroom regularly and completing all assignments from your teachers. They are doing their best to stay in constant communication with all students. If your teacher is not currently using Google Classroom in the primary grades (K-2), please continue communicating through email. Packets for these classrooms should have been delivered by mail or a WCV bus driver. If you are lacking materials, please let me know. I am checking my emails regularly and will respond to both parents and students if you have any questions (or just want to say hello). I wish everyone a very Happy Easter! Keep smiling and stay healthy.

Mrs. Holmes

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians:

Prior to leaving on Friday, both principals conducted a survey in grades 4-12 to determine if any students lacked a personal electronic device to use for instruction at home. Students in need of a device were given the opportunity to borrow a Chromebook.

As of today, all Chromebooks requested have been distributed to students who are enrolled in a grade or class that require digital use (4-12). Everyone should have the most updated hard copy material from their instructors as well. In order to limit the number of visitors at the building, we are no longer taking requests for Chromebooks at this time. In the event we are closed beyond the current expected return date, we will adjust as needed.

As always, if you have questions or concerns do not hesitate to contact the district office.

Thank you,

Mr. Shepardson

post_text: After a literature study on the book Strictly No Elephants by Lisa Manchev Mrs. Smith's and Mrs. Lawton's kindergartners participated in a STEM challenge. Their students needed to use the materials provided to design and build a clubhouse that was off the ground, had a roof, had a way in/out and could hold seven toy animals. They explained their design to the class and had to discuss what worked or what may have been the reasons why their design wasn't stable.

Newport, NY
November 3, 2019 at 9:44 AM ·

11/3/19 8:31 Update

Crews are working on Route 28 south of the village. It is still closed at Mechanic St to White Creek. National Grid is on site at the S-curves. Many people are asking- we do not know when Spectrum is expected to up and running.

White Creek Rd is experiencing a lot off traffic. Please use good sense when traveling that way. Go slow or go another route.

We are getting more info about where and when help is needed in Newport, Middleville and Poland. Many people have silt and debris in their yards and have a lot of cleanup yet to come.

If you see this post and know of those without power or data, please text the update. Thank you.

Stay tuned for more.

shared_text:
Newport, NY
November 2, 2019 at 4:20 PM ·

11/2/19 4:03PM Update

Route 28 is still closed from White Creek Rd. to Mechanic St. in Newport. The National Guard has been deployed to secure the area and clean up the landslide along the parking area. They are working closely with National Grid to get the area ready to reset poles.

State crews are making their way down Route 8 and will be on Route 28 as soon as they can. Route 28 just above North St. is closed and conditions are still dangerous.

White Creek Rd is a work in progress but passable.

The bridge in Middleville is now open.

Crews are working hard on town roads all over Fairfield, Russia, Ohio, Newport, Schuyler and Norway to restore the horrendous road damage we have everywhere. Please be patient and STAY OFF roads that have signs and cones (not all roads will have "Road Closed" signs).

People need help with their clean up. Ask around, let us all know who we can help.

More info as we get it.

State crews are making their way down Route 8 and will be on Route 28 as soon as they can. Route 28 just above North St. is closed and conditions are still dangerous.

White Creek Rd is a work in progress but passable.

The bridge in Middleville is now open.

Crews are working hard on town roads all over Fairfield, Russia, Ohio, Newport, Schuyler and Norway to restore the horrendous road damage we have everywhere. Please be patient and STAY OFF roads that have signs and cones (not all roads will have "Road Closed" signs).

People need help with their clean up. Ask around, let us all know who we can help.

More info as we get it.

post_text:
The Middle/High School Open House will be held this Thursday, September 19 from 6:30-7:30 PM.

Please note that this year we will not be following the 10 period schedule like we have in the past. The Open House will be an open hour for parents to visit any classroom or teacher they would like.

Please understand that this night is dedicated to the exchange of information concerning the children’s educational program; it is not for the discussion of individual students with parents. If parents want to discuss single issues involving their students that should be done in a separate scheduled meeting.

At the main entrance of the building student schedules and a map of the building will be available (if needed). Junior Honor Society students and Student Council members will be working in the building providing assistance to parents who need it.

Also, any parent or guardian who would like to sign up for a Parent Portal account or who need assistance with Parent Portal may visit the Computer Lab in Room 1.

post_text: West Canada Valley was selected as this years ARC Herkimer Person to Person Award Winner. The district received this award for embracing the characteristics of compassion, respect, love and advocacy. The award stems from WCV's involvement in Autism Awareness month, Down Syndrome Awareness Day, volunteer work at the Ronald McDonald house, fundraising for the 21 Club, and the overall inclusive nature of the academic and extracurricular programs at WCV.

post_text: April is Autism Awareness Month. Students in the elementary school were given the opportunity to decorate their own puzzle piece, and share one fun fact about themselves that makes them unique. As we celebrate this month of awareness and acceptance, we see that although every piece is different, each puzzle piece fits, just as every student fits here at WCV.

post_text: Today West Canada Valley hosted a Career Day for our 7th-8th graders. Our Middle School students began the morning with a message about hard-work and staying on the right path from our keynote speaker, John Wallace, Syracuse alumni and NBA basketball player. They then attended six presentations about different career opportunities, including the first female career firefighter in Ilion, an engineer from River Hawk Corporation, a farmer from Jones Family Farm, photographer from Cara Marie Photography, careers in manufacturing from Gehring-Tricot Corporation, and Construction Careers from Mohawk Valley Builders Exchange. Our students enjoyed the experience of learning more about various careers in this area. Thanks to all of our guest presenters and all those that made the event a success!

post_text:
Allysa Dupont Rader from Catholic Charities visited some classrooms in the Middle/High School today to discuss healthy relationships.

Students discussed the differences between healthy and unhealthy relationships and watched several videos that gave examples of unhealthy relationships such as exhibiting jealousy, control, manipulation, etc.

Classes discussed how they should be treating a dating partner and how a dating partner should treat them. Students also explored what to do if they are in a relationship with red flags and how to help a friend who might be in an unhealthy relationship.

post_text:
**ATTENTION ALL PARENTS AND GUARDIANS**

Please be aware that we have had numerous confirmed cases of both the Flu and Strep Throat throughout the MS and HS. If your child is complaining of a sore throat, chills, headache, or any other symptoms associated with the above illnesses, please check them appropriately before sending them to school.

If your child has a fever equal to or greater than 100.4, it is best to keep them at home until they are fever free for 24 hours.

If you have any questions or concerns, please call the health office at Ext. 352.

We appreciate any help you can provide regarding this matter.
